            #[strong Marginal Pdfs for Continuous Random Variables]:

        p.

            The notion of marginal pdfs in connection with discrete random variables was already introduced.  An analogous relationship holds in the continuous case.  Integration replaces the summation notation.

        p.

            #[strong Theorem]

        p.

            Suppose #[i X] and #[i Y] are jointly continuous with joint pdf \(f_{X,Y}(x,y)\).  Then the marginal pdfs, \(f_{X}(x)\) and \(f_{Y}(y)\) are given by $$f_{X}(x)=\int^{\infty}_{-\infty}f(x,y)dy$$

        p.

            for \(-\infty < x < \infty\)

        p.

            and

        p.

            $$f_{Y}(y)=\int^{\infty}_{-\infty}f(x,y)dx$$

        p.

            for \(-\infty < y < \infty\)


        p.

