            #[strong Independent of Random Variables]

        p.

            The concept of independent events that was introduced in your previous class leads quite naturally to a similar definition for independence for random variables.

        p.

            Recall that two events are independent if learning the outcome of one event does not change the probability of the occurrence of the other event.  Two random variables #[i X] and #[i Y] are #[i independent] if, for every two sets #[i A] and #[i B] of real numbers, \(P(X\in A\)  and \(Y \in B\))=P\((X\in A)P(Y\in B)\).

        p.

            If #[i X] and #[i Y] are independent, then for all real numbers #[i x] and #[i y], it must be true that \(P(X \leq x\) and \(Y \leq y)\)=\(P(X\leq x)P(Y\leq y)\)

        p.

            It can be shown that if the above equation is satisfied for all values of #[i x] and #[i y], then #[i X] and #[i Y] must be independent.

        p.


            If \(f_{1}\) and \(f_{2}\) are the marginal p.f.'s or p.d.f's of #[i X] and #[i Y], respectively, then #[i X] and #[i Y] are independent if and only if the following is satisfied for all real numbers #[i x] and #[i y]  $$f_{X,Y}(x,y)=f_{X}(x)f_{Y}(y)$$

        p.

