            #[strong Independence of Random Variables]

        p.

            Just like with the independence of more than 2 events we can extend the concept of more than 2 independent random variables very easily.

        p.

            The #[i n] random variables \(X_{1},...,X_{n}\) are said to be #[i independent] if there are functions \(g_{1}(x_{1}),g_{2}(x_{2}),...,g_{n}(x_{n})\) such that for every \(x_{1},x_{2},...,x_{n}\)
            $$f_{X_{1},X_{2},...,X_{n}}\left(x_{1},x_{2},...,x_{n}\right)=g_{1}(x_{1})g_{2}(x_{2})\cdots g_{n}(x_{n})$$

        p.

            #[strong Random Samples]

        p.

            The above definition of independence as it applies to having $n$ random variables having marginal pdfs that might be quite different.  A special case of this occurs for virtually every set of data collected for statistical analysis.  Suppose an experimenter takes a set of #[i n] measurements \(x_{1},...,x_{n}\), under the same conditions.

        p.

            #[strong Definition]

        p.

            Let \(X_{1},...,X_{n}\) be a set of #[i n] independent random variables, all having the same pdf.  Then \(X_{1},...,X_{n}\) are said to be #[i random sample of size n].

